body: "# Semgrep finding import\n\nSemgrep finding id: 874840456\nRule: javascript.lang.security.audit.detect-non-literal-regexp.detect-non-literal-regexp\nProduct: Code\nSeverity: Medium\nStatus: Open\nConfidence: Low\nCategory: security\nIs Pro Rule: True\nSemgrep autotriage result: False positive\nSemgrep file risk tag: Unspecified\nRepository: unbraind/pm-cli\nBranch: refs/heads/main\nCreated at: 2026-07-03 12:04:25.346290\nLast opened at: 2026-07-03 12:04:25.327920\n\nLinks:\n- Code: https://github.com/unbraind/pm-cli/blob/6f511706628f18743a00a1cfe851e8d1f492684e/src/cli/commands/validate.ts#L1210\n- Semgrep: https://semgrep.dev/orgs/unbrained/findings/874840456\n- Repository: https://github.com/unbraind/pm-cli\n\nRule description:\nRegExp() called with a `value` function argument, this might allow an attacker to cause a Regular Expression Denial-of-Service (ReDoS) within your application as RegExP blocks the main thread. For this reason, it is recommended to use hardcoded regexes instead. If your regex is run on user-controlled input, consider performing input validation or use a regex checking/sanitization library such as https://www.npmjs.com/package/recheck to verify that the regex does not appear vulnerable to ReDoS.\n\nAutotriage reason:\nThis dynamic regex is built from `idPrefix` only after trimming, lowercasing, removing trailing dashes, and escaping all regex metacharacters with `escapeRegExp`, so user-controlled regex syntax does not reach `RegExp()`. In this CLI helper, the remaining variable part only changes a literal prefix match and does not meaningfully create a ReDoS risk, so this is a low-confidence false positive.\n\nImported from downloaded CSV:\n/home/steve/Downloads/Semgrep_Code_Combined_Findings_2026_07_06.csv"
